=== Footnotes ===
*'''a.''' {{Note label|a|a|none}}Pronunciation: The story of the battle has been retold many times in English, from the fifteenth-century [[Agincourt Carol|Agincourt song]] onwards, and an English pronunciation of {{IPA-en|ˈædʒɨn.kɔrt|&lt;!--not a velar N--&gt;}} has become established. [[Merriam-Webster]] has a small audio file [http://www.merriam-webster.com/cgi-bin/audio.pl?ggazin02.wav=Agincourt here]. The modern tendency, however, is to use pronunciations closer to the original French {{IPA-fr|aʒɛ̃kuʁ}}, such as {{IPA|/ˈædʒɨnkɔr/}} or {{IPA|/ˈæʒɨnkʊər/}},&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last=Olausson |first=Lena |coauthors=Sangster, Catherine |others= |title=Oxford BBC Guide to Pronunciation: The Essential Handbook of the Spoken Word|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford, England|year=2006|page=7|quote='''aj'''-in-kor/ˈadʒɪnˌkɔː(r)/ the established anglicization|isbn=978-0-19-280710-6}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Daniel|title=English Pronouncing Dictionary|editors=Roach, Peter ''et al''|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|location=Cambridge, England|year=2003|edition=16|page=12|isbn=9780521017121}}&lt;/ref&gt; as exampled in this interview with [[Juliet Barker]] on ''Meet the Author'', [http://www.meettheauthor.co.uk/bookbites/915.html here].
*'''b.''' {{Note label|b|b|none}}Dates in the fifteenth century are difficult to reconcile with modern calendars: see Barker (2005) pp.&amp;nbsp;225–7 for the way the date of the battle was established.

