      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Other uses}}
{{Bronze Age|210}}

The '''Bronze Age''' is a transitional [[Periodization|period]] between the [[Stone Age]] and [[Iron Age]], characterized by the creation of [[bronze]] from raw materials, the widespread use of bronze tools and weapons, and the continued development of [[pictogram]]ic or [[ideogram]]ic symbols and [[proto-writing]]. In [[archeology]], the ''Bronze Age'' is the 2nd principal period of the [[three-age system]] created by [[Christian Jürgensen Thomsen]]&lt;ref&gt;C. J. Thomsen and [[Jens Jacob Asmussen Worsaae]] first applied the system to artifacts.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Linda Ellis, Archaeological method and theory: an encyclopedia. Page 635.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Kongelige Nordiske oldskriftselskab (Denmark), &amp; GOWER, F. L. (1848). Guide to Northern Archaeology. By the Royal Society of Northern Antiquaries of Copenhagen. Edited for the use of English readers by the Right Honorable the Earl of Ellesmere. James Bain: London; Copenhagen [printed], 1848.&lt;/ref&gt; for classifying and studying ancient societies, particularly the regional societies of the Mediterranean and Near East. The [[archaeological culture]]s are characterized by advance [[metalworking]] and the widespread cultural use of bronze.&lt;ref&gt;Childe, V. G. (1930). The bronze age. New York: The Macmillan Company&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Kelleher, B. D. (1980). Treasures from the Bronze Age of China: An exhibition from the People's Republic of China, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York. New York: Ballantine Books&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Kuijpers, M. H. G. (2008). Bronze Age metalworking in the Netherlands (c. 2000-800 BCE): A research into the preservation of metallurgy related artefacts and the social position of the smith. Leiden: Sidestone Press.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Müller-Lyer, F. C., Lake, E. C., &amp; Lake, H. A. (1921). The history of social development. New York: Alfred A. Knopf.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Ward, J. (1984). Historic ornament: Decorative art &amp; architectural ornament. S.l.: s.n..&lt;/ref&gt; This could either be based on the local smelting of [[copper]] and [[tin]] from [[ore]]s, or trading for bronze from production areas elsewhere.&lt;ref&gt;The naturally occurring ores typically had [[arsenic]] as a common impurity.&lt;/ref&gt; Copper/tin ores are rare, as reflected in the fact that there were no tin bronzes in [[western Asia]] before the [[third millennium BCE]]. Many, though not all, Bronze Age cultures flourished in [[prehistory]].&lt;ref&gt;Burkitt, M. C. (1925). Prehistory: A study of early cultures in Europe and the Mediterranean Basin. Cambridge [Eng.: University Press&lt;/ref&gt; Some cultures developed extensive written records during their Bronze Ages.

A difference between some of the Bronze Age cultures was the [[history of writing|development of the first writings]]. In Egypt ([[hieroglyphs]]), the Near East ([[Cuneiform]]), but also in the Mediterranean, with the Mycenaean culture ([[Linear B]]), had viable systems of written communication. The archaeological findings are evidence of the first written sources.

The end of any particular age is to some extent a convenience for classification purposes, and is also considered to have varied geographically. Worldwide, the Bronze Age generally followed the [[Neolithic|Neolithic age]] (New Stone Age), but in some parts of the world, a [[Copper Age]] followed the Neolithic Age and preceded the Bronze Age. Although the [[Iron Age]] generally followed the Bronze age, in some areas such as in many parts of [[sub-Saharan Africa]], the [[Neolithic|Neolithic age]] was directly followed by the Iron Age, and there was no Bronze Age, as the technology seems to have jumped from stone to iron there.

{{TOC limit|limit=4}}
==History==
{{Human history}}

The term &quot;Bronze Age&quot; is ultimately derived from the &quot;[[Ages of Man]]&quot;, the stages of human existence on the Earth according to [[Greek mythology]]. Of these, the [[Golden Age]] and [[Silver Age]] are categorized by modern historians as mythical, but the Bronze Age as well as the [[Iron Age]] are conceived as having a nucleus of historical validity. The overall period is characterized by the full adoption of bronze in many regions, though the place and time of the introduction and development of bronze technology is not universally synchronous.&lt;ref&gt;Bronze was independently discovered in the [[Maykop culture]] of the [[North Caucasus]] as early as the mid-[[4th millennium BCE]], which would make them the makers of the oldest known bronze. However, the Maykop culture only had [[arsenical bronze]], a naturally occurring alloy. Other regions would utilize bronze and the associated technology at different periods.&lt;/ref&gt; Man-made tin bronze technology requires set production techniques. Tin must be mined (mainly as the tin ore [[cassiterite]]) and smelted separately, then added to molten copper to make the bronze alloy. The Bronze Age was a time of heavy use of metals and of developing trade networks (See ''[[Tin sources and trade in ancient times]]'').

===Near East===
''Southeast Asia / Middle East''
&lt;!-- &quot;Tell Fray&quot; links here --&gt;&lt;!-- &quot;Tuttul&quot; links here --&gt;&lt;!-- &quot;Deir ez-Zor Museum&quot; links here --&gt;
{{Main|Ancient Near East}}

The Bronze Age in the [[Ancient Near East]] began with the rise of [[Sumer]] in the 4th millennium BC. The Ancient Near East is considered the [[cradle of civilization]] and practised intensive year-round agriculture, developed a writing system, invented the potter's wheel, created a centralized government, law codes and empires, and introduced social stratification, slavery and organized warfare. Societies in the region laid the foundations for astronomy and mathematics.

